{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "SPP asset registration resource types",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": null,
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "5c396db3-c0ce-499a-b024-e07f04d4c13a",
        "score": 0.54897213,
        "text": "The document page is from the CAISO Business Practice Manual for Market Operations and outlines various sets and parameters related to system resources. It defines different categories of resources, such as:\n\n- **Non-Dynamic System Resources (S_HPD)**\n- **Proxy Demand Resources (S_HDR)**\n- **RMR Resources (S_RMR)**\n- **Pumped-Storage Hydro Resources (S_PSH)**\n- **Pump Resources (S_PUMP)**\n- **MSS Load Following Resources (S_MSS)**\n- **Resource-Specific System Resources (S_TG)**\n- **Non-Generating Resources (S_NGR)**\n- **EIM Resources (S_EIM)**\n- **EIM Participating Resources (S_EMP)**\n- **EIM Non-Participating Resources (S_EMNPR)**\n\nIt also specifies parameters for NGR resources, including:\n\n- **Registered Minimum and Maximum Load at Generating Side (G_MIN, G_MAX)**\n- **Registered Minimum and Maximum Load at Load Side (L_MIN, L_MAX)**\n- **Registered Minimum and Maximum Capacity (P_MIN, P_MAX)**\n\nThese parameters are assumed to be constant or zero under certain conditions. The document provides a structured framework for categorizing and managing different types of resources within the market operations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Market_Operations_BPM_Appendices/page_43.jpg",
          "page_num": 43,
          "title": "Market Operations BPM Appendices",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7532ca84-ba96-4333-a605-d8e4b37fb9bd",
        "score": 0.5330749,
        "text": "The document is from the PJM Manual 11, focusing on Energy & Ancillary Services Market Operations, specifically the section on Demand Resource Participation. It outlines registration and compensation rules for Curtailment Service Providers (CSPs) in emergency and economic conditions. Key points include:\n\n1. **Registration Types**:\n   - **Pre-Emergency Full (Capacity and Energy)**: Similar to Pre-Emergency Capacity Only but includes emergency energy compensation.\n   - Locations can register for additional services like Economic Regulation-Only or Economic (Energy, SR, SecR, Reg).\n\n2. **Registration Rules**:\n   - A single location can only register as either a Pre-Emergency or Emergency resource for a delivery year.\n\n3. **Curtailment Service Providers (CSPs)**:\n   - CSPs must register in the PJM Markets using a specific tool and maintain accurate registration information.\n   - Critical Natural Gas Infrastructure should not be included in registrations.\n   - CSPs must classify locations by business segment, choosing from categories like Hospitals, Industrial, Residential, etc.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of accurate registration and classification for effective participation in the PJM Markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/protocol/PJM_Manual_11:_Energy_&_Ancillary_Services_Market_Operations/page_168.jpg",
          "page_num": 168,
          "title": "PJM Manual 11: Energy & Ancillary Services Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1c7038a8-59f8-434d-b538-17dc0848a5cf",
        "score": 0.5310223,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for assigning Resource IDs to PDR, RDRR, or PDR-LSR within the CAISO Markets. It describes three types of Resource IDs:\n\n1. **Pre-defined**: These are pre-modeled by CAISO using pre-identified nodes and distribution factors.\n   \n2. **Custom**: These are created upon request for resources not in the existing CAISO model, using customized pricing nodes and distribution factors based on actual load curtailment.\n\n3. **PDR-LSR (Proxy Demand Resource Load Shift Resource)**: This is a single pre-defined resource with two distinct Resource IDs for load curtailment and consumption, registered under Curtailment ID and Consumption ID.\n\nThe naming convention for PDR-LSR includes specific codes for Curtailment and Consumption. Both IDs must be submitted in one file during registration, with consistent BID_DISP_OPT, SC_ID, and effective dates.\n\nElectric Vehicle Supply Equipment (EVSE) is treated as a PDR and follows the same registration process, requiring at least one behind-the-meter or energy storage device when using the EVSE baseline methodology.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/CAISO/protocol/Business_Practice_Manual_for_Demand_Response/page_59.jpg",
          "page_num": 59,
          "title": "Business Practice Manual for Demand Response",
          "year": "",
          "market": "CAISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "9222f86a-4628-4633-bada-78f75edb25ec",
        "score": 0.5208912,
        "text": "The document is a page from the PJM Manual 11, focusing on the participation of demand resources in energy and ancillary services markets. It outlines different scenarios for registration types and their eligibility for various market operations:\n\n1. **Economic (Energy, SR, SecR, Reg)**: Allows participation in energy and ancillary service markets if certified by PJM.\n\n2. **Economic (Energy Only)**: Permits participation only in the energy market, typically when one economic CSP has an Economic Regulation Only registration and another has Economic (Energy Only).\n\n3. **Economic Regulation Only**: Limits participation to the regulation market.\n\n4. **Emergency or Pre-Emergency Capacity Only**: Allows participation in the capacity market as an RPM or FRR resource. No energy payment is received if dispatched for emergency conditions. Suitable for resources with environmental restrictions that can only operate during emergencies.\n\n5. **Emergency or Pre-Emergency Full (Capacity and Energy)**: Similar to Emergency Capacity Only but includes emergency energy compensation. Applicable to resources with environmental restrictions that can only operate during emergencies.\n\nThe table provides a matrix of scenarios (CSP1, CSP2, CSP3) and their eligibility across these registration types.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/protocol/PJM_Manual_11:_Energy_&_Ancillary_Services_Market_Operations/page_167.jpg",
          "page_num": 167,
          "title": "PJM Manual 11: Energy & Ancillary Services Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "1f90b8c3-1061-46a4-934b-66ca24cf09c8",
        "score": 0.51383215,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2009 State of the Market Report for PJM\" and focuses on the capacity market. It outlines different types of capacity resources, which include generation resources, load management resources, and energy efficiency resources. \n\n1. **Capacity Resources**: These resources must meet specific criteria and can be located within or outside PJM, but they must be committed to serving load within PJM.\n\n2. **Generation Resources**: These can be existing or planned generation, or bilateral contracts for unit-specific capacity resources. Existing generation can be offered into RPM Auctions or traded bilaterally if they meet requirements. Planned generation participating in PJM\u2019s Regional Transmission Expansion Planning (RTEP) Process is also eligible.\n\n3. **Load Management Resources**: This involves the ability to reduce metered load upon request. It can be offered as a demand resource (DR) or as an interruptible load for reliability (ILR). DR is offered into RPM Auctions, while ILR is not but receives a final zonal ILR price.\n\n4. **Energy Efficiency Resources**: These can be offered in RPM auctions starting with the 2012/2013 delivery year. An EE resource involves implementing more efficient processes or systems to achieve a continuous reduction in electric energy consumption not reflected in peak load forecasts.\n\nThe document also references specific PJM manuals and sections for further details.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/report/2009/page_577.jpg",
          "page_num": 577,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for PJM",
          "year": 2009,
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

