steps.content:
{
  "success": true,
  "data": {
    "query": "SPP market resource registration types generation demand response storage",
    "num_results": 5,
    "filters_applied": {
      "market": "SPP",
      "data_type": null,
      "year_start": null,
      "year_end": null,
      "range_type": null
    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "1ffbb346-ee29-4818-bcee-c75d0fffe17a",
        "score": 0.6411693,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report discusses the growth of dispatchable demand response resources in the SPP market up to December 1, 2019, and beyond. It includes a figure (Figure 2-25) that illustrates the number of demand response resources and their nameplate capacity (in MW) by year from 2019 to 2021.\n\nKey points include:\n- In 2019, three demand response resources became active, contributing 0.3 MW of capacity.\n- In 2020, 30 additional resources were added, with capacities ranging from 0.1 MW to 20 MW.\n- In 2021, 69 more resources were added, representing 143.8 MW of nameplate capacity.\n- By December 31, 2021, there were 102 demand response resources in the SPP market, totaling 176.2 MW of nameplate capacity.\n\nThe page also mentions that Figure 2-26 (not shown) will present the total generation of dispatchable demand response resources monthly for 2021 and annual totals for the past three years. The overall trend shows significant growth in both the number and capacity of demand response resources in the SPP market over the three-year period.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2021/page_64.jpg",
          "page_num": 64,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3c4a1da7-e16e-48d5-a5fd-0a5d12b97486",
        "score": 0.62809485,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit report focuses on the topic of Demand Response within the Integrated Marketplace.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- At the launch of the Integrated Marketplace in March 2014, six demand response resources were registered, totaling 48 MW of capacity.\n- These resources exited the market in January 2015, resulting in no registered demand response resources until December 2019.\n- In December 2019, three demand response resources with a combined 0.3 MW capacity became active again.\n- Figure 2-25 illustrates the number and nameplate capacity of dispatchable demand response resources from 2021 to 2023.\n- By December 31, 2023, there were 132 demand response resources in the SPP market with a total nameplate capacity of 793 MW.\n- This represents a net loss of eight resources compared to 2022 but a net gain of 431 MW in capacity.\n- In 2023, 64 resources retired, representing 25 MW capacity (mostly 0.1 MW each), while 56 new resources were added, totaling 449 MW capacity.\n- The document notes that Figure 2-26 will show average hourly generation by dispatchable demand response for 2023 and the previous three years.\n\nOverall, the section details the fluctuations in the number and capacity of demand response resources in the SPP market over recent years, highlighting a significant increase in capacity despite a slight decrease in resource count in 2023.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2023/page_59.jpg",
          "page_num": 59,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET 2023",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "841ebe60-e9e4-4c42-89b0-ea092e20ea8b",
        "score": 0.62062037,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. Market Monitoring Unit discusses two main topics related to market operations and recommendations:\n\n1. **Resource Commitment and Decommitment:**\n   - Market software commits resources well in advance based on initial assumptions when the market clears.\n   - These assumptions include load forecasts, wind forecasts, and outage conditions, which can change over time.\n   - Even if conditions change and a resource is no longer profitable or needed, the start-up order is not canceled.\n   - Stakeholders have prioritized developing design changes to economically decommit resources that are no longer needed at the planned start time.\n   - The Market Monitoring Unit (MMU) supports this initiative and recommends developing decommit logic in 2018.\n\n2. **Enhancing Market Rules for Energy Storage Resources:**\n   - With increased wind penetration in the SPP market, there is a growing need for resource flexibility and energy storage to address the rise in negative price occurrences.\n   - Stored energy resources can provide flexibility and help reduce negative prices, but current SPP tariffs do not facilitate their integration.\n   - A new market design is needed to capture the benefits of energy storage technologies.\n   - Although discussions have occurred about incorporating energy storage, tariff language development to support these resources has not yet happened.\n   - The lack of effective market design is seen as a barrier to integrating storage resources.\n   - Enhancing market rules will enable these resources to enter the market, addressing negative prices and adding flexibility.\n   - The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) issued an order in February 2018 requiring RTOs/ISOs to develop market rules promoting energy storage.\n   - The MMU agrees with FERC\u2019s directive and looks forward to further discussions on this topic.\n\nThe page includes a reference link to the FERC order and is part of the \"State of the Market 2017\" report.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2017/page_207.jpg",
          "page_num": 207,
          "title": "STATE OF THE MARKET",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a87bdb11-60b7-4c48-a8de-a987eb290c97",
        "score": 0.62031573,
        "text": "This document page from the \"SPP 2012 State of the Market Report\" covers two main topics: Ramp and Capacity, and Resource Utilization by Status.\n\n1. Ramp and Capacity:\n- The section discusses the ramp rates in the SPP EIS Market, which are shown in Figure II.21.\n- Ramp is standardized by available capacity and compared to average online capacity.\n- The total system ramp showed an upward trend in 2012.\n- Monthly values reveal a cyclical pattern of available ramp.\n- Peaking units used during summer peak periods generally have higher ramp rates.\n- The long-term trend is upward, contributing positively to reducing ramp breaches since the market's inception.\n- Figure II.21 includes two charts: one showing monthly ramp and average online capacity for 2011 and 2012, and another showing annual ramp and capacity from 2007 to 2012.\n\n2. Resource Utilization by Status:\n- Market participants can modify how a resource functions by selecting a status type.\n- The \"Available\" status is unique in allowing full utilization of a resource, enabling it to change output and set system price.\n- Available units are crucial for resolving congestion, alleviating operational constraints, and achieving least-cost market dispatch.\n- Resources with statuses other than Available cannot be directed by the market system.\n- Other status types include manual, self-scheduled, unavailable, and supplemental.\n- Manual status was discontinued in late February 2011 and replaced with options such as Exigent Conditions, Intermittent, Qualifying Facility, Quick Start, Shut Down, and Start.\n\nOverall, the page provides insights into system ramp trends and the operational flexibility of resources in the market through status designations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2012/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "2012 State of the Market",
          "year": 2012,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "c1e0702e-ee51-4839-9663-4b551858ed4e",
        "score": 0.61629295,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. discusses the utilization of different status types for market resources and their impact on market operations.\n\n**Status Type Utilization:**\n- Market Participants can modify resource control parameters by selecting a status type in their resource plans, which dictates how the resource functions.\n- In 2010, there were five status types: available, unavailable, self-scheduled, manual, and supplemental.\n- In late February 2011, the \"manual\" status was discontinued and replaced with several new types: exigent conditions, intermittent, qualifying facility, quick start, shut down, start up, and testing.\n- Only the \"available\" status allows full market utilization of a resource, enabling it to adjust output and set system prices.\n- \"Manual\" status indicates uncontrollable resources that cannot set prices and are dispatched at their last known output.\n- Self-scheduled resources operate based on predetermined output levels regardless of market conditions.\n- \"Unavailable\" status means the resource is offline and not usable by the market or participant.\n- \"Supplemental\" status means the resource is offline but can come online within ten minutes.\n- Available status units are most valuable to the market as they can respond quickly to instructions, helping resolve congestion and operational constraints.\n\n**Generation by Status Type:**\n- Most generation comes from market-available resources, allowing efficient operation and resolution of constraints.\n- The \"Start-up, Shut-down, and Test\" category was introduced in February 2011.\n- Intermittent resources are gaining importance in the EIS Market, with status types separated to categorize generation properly.\n- There is a noted steady decline in self-dispatched generation.\n\nOverall, the page explains how different resource status types affect market participation, resource dispatch, and generation efficiency, highlighting changes made in 2011 to improve categorization and market operation.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2011/page_65.jpg",
          "page_num": 65,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

