        "score": 0.62031573,
        "text": "This document page from the \"SPP 2012 State of the Market Report\" covers two main topics: Ramp and Capacity, and Resource Utilization by Status.\n\n1. Ramp and Capacity:\n- The section discusses the ramp rates in the SPP EIS Market, which are shown in Figure II.21.\n- Ramp is standardized by available capacity and compared to average online capacity.\n- The total system ramp showed an upward trend in 2012.\n- Monthly values reveal a cyclical pattern of available ramp.\n- Peaking units used during summer peak periods generally have higher ramp rates.\n- The long-term trend is upward, contributing positively to reducing ramp breaches since the market's inception.\n- Figure II.21 includes two charts: one showing monthly ramp and average online capacity for 2011 and 2012, and another showing annual ramp and capacity from 2007 to 2012.\n\n2. Resource Utilization by Status:\n- Market participants can modify how a resource functions by selecting a status type.\n- The \"Available\" status is unique in allowing full utilization of a resource, enabling it to change output and set system price.\n- Available units are crucial for resolving congestion, alleviating operational constraints, and achieving least-cost market dispatch.\n- Resources with statuses other than Available cannot be directed by the market system.\n- Other status types include manual, self-scheduled, unavailable, and supplemental.\n- Manual status was discontinued in late February 2011 and replaced with options such as Exigent Conditions, Intermittent, Qualifying Facility, Quick Start, Shut Down, and Start.\n\nOverall, the page provides insights into system ramp trends and the operational flexibility of resources in the market through status designations.",
