    },
    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "90d146f2-456d-4949-89c5-7d39db5dc204",
        "score": 0.6629457,
        "text": "This document page provides an overview of the participants in the SPP (Southwest Power Pool) Integrated Marketplace as of the end of 2014. It states that 134 entities were involved in the marketplace, marking a significant increase from the 102 participants in the predecessor EIS Market in 2013. Unlike the EIS Market, which required participants to own physical assets like generation or load, the SPP Marketplace is open to both financial and physical asset owners.\n\nThe market participants are categorized into several groups: investor-owned utilities, cooperatives, municipals, state agencies, independent power producers, and financial-only participants. The document highlights that the number of Independent Power Producers is notably high, primarily because most wind producers fall into this category. Additionally, some market participants, called agents, represent multiple individual resource owners who would otherwise be classified under different categories such as municipal, cooperative, or state agency.\n\nA pie chart titled \"Figure 2\u20132 Distribution of Market Participants with Resources by Type\" visually represents the distribution of these categories as of December 31, 2014. The chart shows that Independent Power Producers constitute the largest segment, followed by municipals, investor-owned utilities, cooperatives, state agencies, and agents.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2014/page_25.jpg",
          "page_num": 25,
          "title": "2014 State of the Market",
          "year": 2014,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "7532ca84-ba96-4333-a605-d8e4b37fb9bd",
        "score": 0.66274434,
        "text": "The document is from the PJM Manual 11, focusing on Energy & Ancillary Services Market Operations, specifically the section on Demand Resource Participation. It outlines registration and compensation rules for Curtailment Service Providers (CSPs) in emergency and economic conditions. Key points include:\n\n1. **Registration Types**:\n   - **Pre-Emergency Full (Capacity and Energy)**: Similar to Pre-Emergency Capacity Only but includes emergency energy compensation.\n   - Locations can register for additional services like Economic Regulation-Only or Economic (Energy, SR, SecR, Reg).\n\n2. **Registration Rules**:\n   - A single location can only register as either a Pre-Emergency or Emergency resource for a delivery year.\n\n3. **Curtailment Service Providers (CSPs)**:\n   - CSPs must register in the PJM Markets using a specific tool and maintain accurate registration information.\n   - Critical Natural Gas Infrastructure should not be included in registrations.\n   - CSPs must classify locations by business segment, choosing from categories like Hospitals, Industrial, Residential, etc.\n\nThe document emphasizes the importance of accurate registration and classification for effective participation in the PJM Markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/protocol/PJM_Manual_11:_Energy_&_Ancillary_Services_Market_Operations/page_168.jpg",
          "page_num": 168,
          "title": "PJM Manual 11: Energy & Ancillary Services Market Operations",
          "year": "",
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
