    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "4c2f0e00-e284-457c-955b-b995f0112520",
        "score": 0.590575,
        "text": "The document is a section from the PJM Manual 27, focusing on Open Loop Hybrid and Energy Storage Resource Charging Energy. It provides an overview of accounting procedures for these resources within the PJM Energy, Capacity, and Ancillary Services markets. \n\nKey points include:\n\n1. **Energy Storage Resources**: These are capable of storing electric energy for later use, participating in various PJM markets. Examples include pumped storage hydroelectric plants, batteries, and flywheels.\n\n2. **Hybrid Resources**: Composed of multiple components, such as a generation component and a storage component, operating as a single integrated resource.\n\n3. **Charging Energy**: Energy purchased for storage and later resale is billed at the Locational Marginal Price. Different categories of charging energy incur different charges:\n   - **Direct Charging Energy**: Energy purchased from the PJM Interchange Energy Market for resale or lost to conversion inefficiencies. It includes:\n     - **Dispatched Charging Energy**: Energy received from the grid as per PJM dispatch for providing services in the markets.\n\nThe document also references Manual 28, Section 22, for further details on model participants.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/protocol/PJM_Manual_27:_Open_Access_Transmission_Tariff_Accounting/page_48.jpg",
          "page_num": 48,
          "title": "PJM Manual 27: Open Access Transmission Tariff Accounting",
          "year": "",
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "73b960e9-3c90-4cda-a7e0-d4e358f87f1b",
        "score": 0.5703708,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool (SPP) 2011 State of the Market Report focuses on \"Energy Delivery,\" specifically the subsection \"Transmission Service.\"\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The SPP Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) is mandated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) to manage and regulate energy flow across the transmission system within its territory.\n- SPP member companies have agreed to let SPP administer their transmission systems under the SPP Open Access Transmission Tariff.\n- The Tariff outlines regulations on how Market Participants are compensated for using the transmission system and the rules governing its use.\n- Participants wanting to use the transmission system must adhere to provisions in the SPP Tariff, Market Protocols, and Business Practices.\n- Market Participants collaborate with SPP to ensure that transmission service requests are approved up to the maximum allowable amount while maintaining system reliability and security.\n- Changes in transmission system flows can signal larger economic shifts or the need for system modifications.\n- Metrics are used to detect these changes, though the specific metrics are not detailed on this page.\n\nOverall, the page explains the regulatory framework, operational protocols, and collaborative efforts involved in managing transmission services within the SPP region.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2011/page_76.jpg",
          "page_num": 76,
          "title": "2011 State of the Market",
          "year": 2011,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "b286ab4b-50d1-4412-8f1b-8054ff641e76",
        "score": 0.56972224,
        "text": "This document page from the Southwest Power Pool (SPP) 2010 State of the Market Report focuses on \"Energy Delivery,\" specifically the subsection \"Transmission Service.\"\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The SPP Regional Transmission Organization (RTO) is mandated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) to manage and regulate energy flow across the transmission system within its territory.\n- SPP member companies have agreed to let SPP administer their transmission systems under the SPP Open Access Transmission Tariff.\n- The Tariff outlines regulations on how Market Participants are compensated for using the transmission system and the rules governing its use.\n- Participants wanting to use the transmission system must adhere to provisions in the Tariff, Market Protocols, and Business Practices.\n- Market Participants collaborate with SPP to ensure the approval of the maximum amount of transmission service requests while maintaining system reliability and security.\n- Changes in demand patterns through transmission system flows can signal larger economic shifts or modifications to the transmission system.\n- Specific metrics are used to detect these types of changes.\n\nOverall, the page explains the regulatory framework, operational protocols, and monitoring mechanisms that govern the use and management of the transmission system within the SPP region.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/SPP/report/2010/page_69.jpg",
          "page_num": 69,
          "title": "2010 State of the Market",
          "year": 2010,
          "market": "SPP",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "146fe7ad-13b0-457f-aa68-2db2b492526a",
        "score": 0.5613649,
        "text": "The document is a table of contents from the \"PJM Manual 27: Open Access Transmission Tariff Accounting.\" It outlines various sections related to transmission service accounting and billing:\n\n- **Section 5** covers Network Integration Transmission Service Accounting, detailing service charges, credits, and business rules for pricing and settlement.\n- **Section 6** focuses on Point-to-Point Transmission Service Accounting, including an overview, charges, and credits.\n- **Section 7** addresses Black Start Service Accounting, with information on service credits and charges.\n- **Section 8** discusses Open Loop Hybrid & Energy Storage Resource Charging Energy, including overviews and charges for different types of energy.\n- **Section 9** provides an overview of the billing process.\n- **Section 10** deals with Transmission Enhancement Accounting, covering overviews and credits.\n\nThe document is marked as Revision 102, effective from January 23, 2025.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/protocol/PJM_Manual_27:_Open_Access_Transmission_Tariff_Accounting/page_3.jpg",
          "page_num": 3,
          "title": "PJM Manual 27: Open Access Transmission Tariff Accounting",
          "year": "",
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3d1ef1a0-d449-4fd7-bd92-95a9ce2a4699",
        "score": 0.55974656,
        "text": "The document is a revision summary for PJM Manual 27, effective January 23, 2025. Key updates include:\n\n- Spelling and grammar corrections in Sections 2, 3, 4, 5, and 8.\n- Removal of outdated references to Expansion Costs and RTO Start-up Cost Recovery in Section 1.2.\n- Deletion of language in Section 4.1 about PJM's transmission service types, as it was too specific.\n- Clarification in Section 2.2.1.3 that Point to Point transactions for export are included in Schedule 9-3 Market Support Service Charges.\n- Added descriptions in Sections 5.2.1 and 5.2.2 for determining Non-Zone Network load responsibility for Network Customers.\n- Removal of references to Firm Point-to-point load service customers in Section 5.3.\n- Addition of references to Manual 28, Section 22, for information on open loop hybrid and ESR Model Participants in Section 8.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/PJM/protocol/PJM_Manual_27:_Open_Access_Transmission_Tariff_Accounting/page_6.jpg",
          "page_num": 6,
          "title": "PJM Manual 27: Open Access Transmission Tariff Accounting",
          "year": "",
          "market": "PJM",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

